        slug: 'philosophy-of-space-and-time',
        title: 'Space Architecture: Designing Beyond Earth',
        category: 'Space Design',
        description: 'As humanity prepares to live on the Moon and Mars, architects and engineers face radical new design challenges in harsh, airless environments.',
        color: 'from-slate-500 to-blue-900',
        icon: '🚀',
        tags: ['Space Habitat', 'Mars Design', 'Off-World Living'],
        imageUrl: 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1446776709462-d6dcc77c0b6f?w=800&q=80',
        content: [
            { heading: 'The Challenge of Off-World Habitation', body: "Designing for space is design pushed to its extremes. No atmosphere, extreme temperature swings (from -100°C to +100°C on the Moon), radiation bombardment, micrometeorite impacts, and psychological isolation — every design decision is life or death. Unlike buildings on Earth, space habitats must function as sealed life-support systems while remaining light enough to launch." },
            { heading: 'Lunar Architecture', body: "NASA's Artemis base camp and ESA's Moon Village concepts envision modular habitats partially buried underground or inside lava tubes for radiation and temperature shielding. 3D printing with lunar regolith (Moon rock dust) could fabricate walls and structures using local materials, dramatically reducing the mass that must be launched from Earth — a crucial economic and logistical consideration." },
            { heading: 'Mars Colony Design', body: "Mars presents different but equally extreme challenges. Its thin CO₂ atmosphere provides no radiation protection. Dust storms can last months. Days are 24.6 hours, seasons are double Earth's. Habitats must support agriculture, manufacturing, and social life for years without resupply. SpaceX's Starship is designed to deliver the massive payloads required to establish a self-sustaining Martian colony." },
            { heading: 'Human Factors in Space Design', body: "Prolonged microgravity or partial gravity affects human physiology — bones lose density, muscles atrophy, fluids shift to the upper body. Psychological research on Antarctic stations, submarines, and ISS missions informs habitat design: private sleeping quarters, communal spaces, natural light simulation, plants, and contact with Earth are critical for crew well-being on long missions." },
            { heading: 'Technologies Enabling Space Habitation', body: "Closed-loop life support systems — like the ISS's ability to recycle 90% of water — must approach 100% efficiency on Mars. In-situ resource utilization (ISRU) extracts water from ice deposits and oxygen from the Martian atmosphere. Nuclear power provides energy independent of solar intensity. Advanced materials, additive manufacturing, and AI-driven monitoring will make off-world habitation increasingly viable." },
        ],
